n eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Coke was born in 1220, in Crostwick, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. He married Felice Cork before 1240. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1279, in his hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1220–1279":"1220–1279","1221–1303":"1221–1303","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1303":"1303","1279":"1279","1221":"1221","1220":"1220","before 1240":"enne 1240","1240":"1240","Crostwick, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Crostwick, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1220–1279":"1220–1279","1221–1303":"1221–1303","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1303":"1303","1279":"1279","1221"